    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-11T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-11T12:00:00-05:00" n="951"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d951">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 European War/10–1144: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Portugal</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lisbon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-11T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 11, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 11—4:07 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3110. Sampaio told me today that in response to an urgent request from Campbell
                    for a statement concerning war criminals which the British Government could use
                    in replying to a Parliamentary question which would be put today, Dr. Salazar
                    addressed to Campbell along the following lines: The Portuguese Government has
                    already made clear its attitude from the juridical and political point of view
                    concerning the question of giving asylum to war criminals. However, in <pb
                        facs="1454" n="1440" xml:id="pg_1440"/> order to avoid the possibility of
                    any misunderstanding it wishes to state that it follows from the above that the
                    Portuguese Government will not permit the use of the right of asylum to protect
                    any persons from the proper demands of justice as established by competent
                    national or international authorities.</p>
                <p>The foregoing is not a direct quotation but is an approximation of what Sampaio
                    told me.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Norweb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
